\section{Dynamics of Linear Perturbations}
The dynamics of linear perturbations is presented in Fourier space. Instead of the coordinate wavenumber, $k$, a reduced dimensionless wavenumber is introduced, 
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathrm{K}\equiv\frac{k}{aH},
\end{eqnarray}
so that $K$ can easily recognize the sub-(super)-horizon regimes. In the synchronous gauge, the non-zero metric perturbations are $\delta g_{ij}=a^2 h_{ij}$. In an orthonormal basis $\{\hat k, \hat l, \hat m\}$ in $k$-space, the spatial matrix $h_{ij}$ is further decomposed as 
$h_{ij}=\frac{1}{3}h\delta_{ij}+h_{\parallel}\sigma_{ij}+{{h}}^{\scriptscriptstyle\textrm{{V}}}\cdot v_{ij}+{{h}}^{\scriptscriptstyle\textrm{{T}}}\cdot e_{ij}$, where the notations ${{h}}^{\scriptscriptstyle\textrm{{V}}}$ and ${{h}}^{\scriptscriptstyle\textrm{{T}}}$ contain the two vector and the two tensor polarization states respectively, and the dot product has to be understood as a sum over the polarization states.  Instead of $h$, we use the combination $6\eta\equiv h_{\parallel}-h$. The basis matrices are $\sigma_{ij} =\hat{k}_{i}\hat{k}_{j}-\frac{1}{3}\delta_{ij}$ for the longitudinal traceless mode, ${{v}}^{\scriptscriptstyle\textrm{{(1)}}}_{ij}=2\hat{k}_{(i}\hat{l}_{j)}$ and ${{v}}^{\scriptscriptstyle\textrm{{(2)}}}_{ij}=2\hat{k}_{(i}\hat{m}_{j)}$ for the vector modes and $e_{ij}^{\times}=2\hat{l}_{[i}\hat{m}_{j]}$, $e_{ij}^{+}=\hat{l}_{i}\hat{l}_{j}-\hat{m}_{i}\hat{m}_{j}$ for the tensor modes. In the conformal Newtonian gauge,  $\delta{g_{00}}=-2a^{2}\psi$ and t $\delta{g_{ij}}=-2a^{2}\phi\delta_{ij}$ (the tensor and vector modes remain the same in both gauges). An additional scalar degree of freedom arises at the perturbative level from the non-vanishing $f_\mathcal{R}^\prime$, given by\footnote{With the gauge invariant notation the perturbed Ricci scalar reads $\delta\mathcal{R}=-6H^2(W+4X-\tfrac{1}{3}K^2(Y-2Z)-{{\bar{\epsilon}}}_{\scriptscriptstyle{\textrm{{H}}}}T)$. The fact that $T$ appears explicitly in the expression of $\delta\mathcal{R}$ indicates that this is not a gauge invariant quantity.\label{fn:deltaR}}

